Guild halls are similar to Option III custom houses. 

-Guild halls can have locked doors, but they will still be pickable.
-There can be multiple drop rooms. Drop rooms after the first have their own room. This means that Guild halls can have more than four rooms. Pricing for these rooms is the same as a townhouse.
-For food items, Guild halls can have either the innkeeper or another mobile be a shopkeeper to sell food. They will only buy food items.

Age of Legends Clan Housing Options 

A member of a clan can get housing in a clan building. The housing is one room only (like a townhouse) and follows the townhouse pricing. These rooms will be available on a first come, first serve basis as with the townhouses. Only a limited number (4) will be created in each area. 

1. Study/Barrack rooms will be added to the Keeps. Only a member of the KoS (someone with that flag set) will be allowed to purchase one of the rooms. 

2. Study/Sleeping rooms will be added to the Towers. Only a member of the Conclave (someone with the flag set) will be allowed to purchase one of these rooms. 

3. Other clans formed by the players can have similar housing made available under in the following manner. (Definition/Approval/etc for player formed clans is done by the social department.) - The clan building will be initially handled as a 4 room custom house with one room being the drop room for one person, most likely the founding member. All the rules and benefits of the 4 room custom house apply here (pricing, obj allowance, location selection, etc). - Once a clan building is created members of the clan can add barrack type rooms that follow the townhouse guidelines. So for each additional member one barrack/bedroom (a drop room) can be added and will follow the townhouse pricing. The key difference is that it will be part of the clan house, not on a city street. 
- A maximum of two of the objects created for the clan house can be wearable. 
- Clan houses can have a shopkeeper mob to provide access to items, if desired. 

ex: Takhisis forms the Evil Pantheon clan. She pays 60p for a four room house. Her four rooms consist of a kitchen, a meeting room, a lounge/living room, and her bedroom. With her purchase she can get no more than 4 objects. She chooses a key for the entrance in the shape of a crescent-shaped medallion, kender steak, and a glass of red wine (which must be stored in a pantry, her fourth object) as her objects. The monthly costs taxes cost her 60p. She can elect to charge any members she gets dues to cover the costs for maintaining the common areas. That's between the players. 

Chemosh comes from chaos to join her Evil Pantheon clan. He buys a bedroom for 20p (the townhouse rate) and it is added to the clan building. His monthly cost is 14p. 

Sargonnas comes along and does the same. 2op to add his room, 14p per month. Zeboim and Nuitari are born. To save money Takhisis proposes they share a room. That will never work, so they each need their own room. Yes, that's right. Only one char per drop/bedroom. Morgion and Hiddukel also join and get their rooms. Hiddukel tries to strike a deal, but alas the rules are the rules. 

Members of the clan enjoy access to the building's common areas. They can all grab a kender steak and/or some wine from the pantry. And they can all get a key. 

-If clan members do not want their own drop room, they can still be given access to the main clan areas and the innkeep mob so that they may rent at the clan house. 


NOTE: The same location restrictions/rules apply. Which means that custom clan housing (#4 above) wouldn't be able to be added to the city or within 20 rooms of a start city. All locations are subject to approval.

