ROLEPLAY  RP

Age of Legends is a Role-Playing mud.  What this means in 
practice is that you should act "in character" at all times, if possible.
For those of you who have played any role-playing games, you should
be somewhat familiar with this.  For those of you who are not, think
of it as acting out the part of your character.  Pretend you really
are the race you chose, with the attitudes and impressions of others
that would be appropriate for that character concept.

If you must talk out of character (ooc), please use the OOC command.
As a new player, we understand you might have questions that you cannot
phrase in an appropriate in-character context - that's what OOC is for.    

What does this mean?  It means you should never discuss
things like hp/hit points, stats, levels, experience, real life issues,
or anything a "character" would not be aware of.  Directions should be
given in paces - for instance, the Post Office is one pace south and
one pace east from the Town Square.  You can talk about the knowledge
or life experience a character has, especially in relation to other
characters, but shouldn't give these experiences a numeric value.

Here's a brief list of common mud phrases and good rp-equivalents:

afk - asleep, daydreaming, napping
linkdead - unconscious, blacked out
skills - just say something about "trying to become more skilled in x's use"
levels - again, you can say "I'm more knowledgeable than X" or "I feel as
though I have learned something", etc.
I'm a newbie - I'm new to Kalaman

Feel free to create whatever background you like for your character, and
flesh this out as much as you are comfortable with.

If you have further questions, feel free to ask any of the immortals here. 

See also: DRAGONLANCE
#
SHOPS

Shops are places where the adventurer may purchase equipment for his quests,
and where he may sell his treasure if he should manage to survive the perils
with his life and sanity intact.  Many shops trade only in a specific type of
merchandise.  Thus, a baker may well refuse to buy your armor, even if it is
of high quality!

To some people, the prospect of obtaining the entire inventory of a shop by
murdering the keeper may appear tempting - but beware: The shopkeepers are 
often rugged, capable people; roughened by years of trading and, indeed, 
surviving in a world where the only safe prospect is death in the end.

See also: BUY, SELL, LIST, VALUE
#
WARRIOR FIGHTER

Warriors are known to have more strength than the average player.  This makes 
them better at hand-to-hand combat, as they possess skills of violence and 
fighting unequaled by the members of any other class.  However, they lack 
the ability to use magic of any sort.  As they often have a need to use 
versatility and resourcefulness in there travels, fighters will use virtually 
any item they come across.  Warriors must possess at least an average 
strength for the use of the heavy weapons and armor that are commonly used 
in combat.

See also: PRACTICE
#
RPFACTOR

RP factor, or roleplay factor, is an award given to players for role-playing
with other players and often for participation in staff-run events.  Each point
of your roleplay factor will provide a bonus to experience earned.    

See also: RP, EXPERIENCE
#
TICK

A "tick" is a representation of time within the confines of the game.  One
tick is the equivalent of one hour within the game.  While resting, you will
memorize spells more efficiently, as well as regenerate both health and movement 
at an increased rate per in-game hour.    
#
REFLECT


In this game, spells and skills will not improve beyond a certain point
without repeated use.  While resting, it is possible for a character to
reflect on the skills they have used and to discern a way to utilize them
more effectively.

See also: SKILLS, PRACTICE
#
HITPOINTS HP

&cHitpoints&n are the numerical representation of your general state of
health.  You can enable a display that will allow you a constant look at your
hitpoints by typing "prompt all".  Your HP will be the first number on the
left, followed by the letter H.  

For example: &c175H&n 89V.    

See also: MOVEMENT, PROMPT
#
MOVEMENT MV

&cMovement&n is the numerical representation of how far your character can
travel at any given time.  Keep in mind, that some terrain may be harder to
traverse than others, and thus may cost you more movement points to pass
through some areas than others.  

Using the "prompt all" command, you can have your movement points, along with 
your hit points displayed persistantly.  It will be the second set of numbers, 
followed by the letter V.  

For example: 128H &c89V&n

See also: HITPOINTS, PROMPT
#
TERRAIN

Terrain is a term used to describe the general geographical features of an 
area.  Different types of terrain have different effects on movement, and in 
certain situations, other things as well.  

For example: crossing a mountain range is far more taxing than strolling down 
a paved city street.  Or if you find yourself underwater, you'll find dragging 
yourself through it to be exhausting as well.  And if you're going for a swim, 
remember that you still need to breathe, and you can't do that under leagues of 
water.    

